   "source": [
    "# The Particle Transformer: Physics-Informed Attention\n",
    "\n",
    "**ML4FP Tutorial -- Notebook 3**\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "In Notebooks 1 and 2 we built standard transformers for jet classification. They work, but they treat all particle pairs identically -- the model has to learn from scratch which particles are physically related.\n",
    "\n",
    "The **Particle Transformer** (ParT) encodes known physics relationships directly into the attention mechanism. It provides Lorentz-invariant pairwise quantities -- angular distance, momentum sharing, invariant mass -- as an additive bias in the attention scores. This gives the model a strong prior on which particle pairs matter, without restricting what it can learn.\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook does not involve any training. We will:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Work through the pairwise physics features that inform ParT's attention\n",
    "2. See how the interaction bias modifies the attention formula\n",
    "3. Explore pre-trained model weights\n",
    "4. Review what interpretability studies reveal about what ParT learns internally\n",
    "\n",
    "**References:**\n",
    "- Qu et al., \"Particle Transformer for Jet Tagging\" ([arXiv:2202.03772](https://arxiv.org/abs/2202.03772))\n",
    "- Wang et al., \"Interpreting Transformers for Jet Tagging\" ([arXiv:2412.03673](https://arxiv.org/abs/2412.03673))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Why a new architecture?\n",
    "\n",
    "The transformer from Notebook 1 computes attention scores purely from learned embeddings of each particle's features. It has to discover on its own that angular proximity, momentum sharing, and invariant mass are important signals for classifying jets.\n",
    "\n",
    "We already know these relationships matter. The Particle Transformer encodes this domain knowledge directly into the architecture, yielding better performance, more data-efficient training, and more interpretable internal representations."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
