  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Computing All Four Pairwise Features\n",
    "\n",
    "We compute all four pairwise feature matrices and compare a **QCD jet** (ordinary quark/gluon radiation) with an **Hbb jet**."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def compute_all_pairwise_features(pt, eta, phi, energy):\n",
    "    \"\"\"Compute all 4 pairwise features used by the Particle Transformer.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Returns: dict with keys 'deltaR', 'kT', 'z', 'm2'\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    n = len(pt)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # 1. Delta R\n",
    "    deta = eta[:, None] - eta[None, :]\n",
    "    dphi = phi[:, None] - phi[None, :]\n",
    "    dphi = np.mod(dphi + np.pi, 2 * np.pi) - np.pi\n",
    "    deltaR = np.sqrt(deta**2 + dphi**2)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # 2. kT = min(pT_i, pT_j) * deltaR\n",
    "    pt_min = np.minimum(pt[:, None], pt[None, :])\n",
    "    kT = pt_min * deltaR\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # 3. z = min(pT_i, pT_j) / (pT_i + pT_j)\n",
    "    pt_sum = pt[:, None] + pt[None, :]\n",
    "    pt_sum = np.where(pt_sum > 0, pt_sum, 1.0)  # avoid division by zero\n",
    "    z = pt_min / pt_sum\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # 4. Invariant mass squared: m^2 = (p_i + p_j)^2\n",
    "    # = 2 * (E_i * E_j - px_i*px_j - py_i*py_j - pz_i*pz_j)\n",
    "    # (assuming massless particles)\n",
    "    px = pt * np.cos(phi)\n",
    "    py = pt * np.sin(phi)\n",
    "    pz = pt * np.sinh(eta)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    m2 = (2 * (energy[:, None] * energy[None, :]\n",
    "              - px[:, None] * px[None, :]\n",
    "              - py[:, None] * py[None, :]\n",
    "              - pz[:, None] * pz[None, :]))\n",
    "    m2 = np.maximum(m2, 0)  # clip small negatives from numerical precision\n",
    "    \n",
    "    return {'deltaR': deltaR, 'kT': kT, 'z': z, 'm2': m2}\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def get_jet_features(idx, n_show=30):\n",
    "    \"\"\"Extract features for the top n_show particles (by pT) of jet idx.\"\"\"\n",
    "    pt_  = x_particles[idx, 0, :]\n",
    "    eta_ = x_particles[idx, 1, :]\n",
    "    phi_ = x_particles[idx, 2, :]\n",
    "    E_   = x_particles[idx, 3, :]\n",
    "    real = pt_ > 0\n",
    "    n_real = min(real.sum(), n_show)\n",
    "    order = np.argsort(-pt_[real])[:n_real]\n",
    "    return pt_[real][order], eta_[real][order], phi_[real][order], E_[real][order]\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# Find one QCD jet and one Hbb jet\n",
    "qcd_idx = np.where(y[:, 0] == 1)[0][5]   # label_QCD\n",
    "hbb_idx = np.where(y[:, 1] == 1)[0][5]   # label_Hbb\n",
    "\n",
    "# Compute for both jets (use top 30 particles for clearer visualization)\n",
    "n_show = 30\n",
    "qcd_feats = compute_all_pairwise_features(*get_jet_features(qcd_idx, n_show))\n",
    "hbb_feats = compute_all_pairwise_features(*get_jet_features(hbb_idx, n_show))\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"QCD jet index: {qcd_idx} ({x_particles[qcd_idx, 0, x_particles[qcd_idx, 0, :] > 0].shape[0]} total particles)\")\n",
    "print(f\"Hbb jet index: {hbb_idx} ({x_particles[hbb_idx, 0, x_particles[hbb_idx, 0, :] > 0].shape[0]} total particles)\")\n",
    "print(f\"Showing top {n_show} particles by pT\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Visualize all 4 pairwise features: QCD vs Hbb side by side\n",
    "feature_names = ['$\\\\Delta R$', '$k_T$ [GeV]', '$z$', '$m^2$ [GeV$^2$]']\n",
    "feature_keys = ['deltaR', 'kT', 'z', 'm2']\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(4, 2, figsize=(12, 18))\n",
    "\n",
    "for row, (name, key) in enumerate(zip(feature_names, feature_keys)):\n",
    "    for col, (feats, jet_type) in enumerate([(qcd_feats, 'QCD jet'), (hbb_feats, 'Hbb jet')]):\n",
    "        ax = axes[row, col]\n",
    "        matrix = feats[key]\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # Use log scale for kT and m2 (they span many orders of magnitude)\n",
    "        if key in ['kT', 'm2']:\n",
    "            matrix_plot = np.log10(matrix + 1e-6)\n",
    "            label = f'log$_{{10}}$({name})'\n",
    "        else:\n",
    "            matrix_plot = matrix\n",
    "            label = name\n",
    "        \n",
    "        im = ax.imshow(matrix_plot, cmap='viridis', aspect='equal')\n",
    "        ax.set_title(f'{jet_type}: {label}', fontsize=13)\n",
    "        ax.set_xlabel('Particle j')\n",
    "        ax.set_ylabel('Particle i')\n",
    "        plt.colorbar(im, ax=ax, shrink=0.8)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### What to Look For\n",
    "\n",
     Here the particles are sorted by $p_T$, so the upper-left corner involves the hardest particles in the jet.\n",
    "\n",
    "- **$\\Delta R$**: small values near the diagonal mean nearby particles in angle. In the Hbb example, the near-diagonal band is smoother and more organized; in the QCD example, the pattern is patchier, with several isolated wide-angle particles appearing as bright stripes.\n",
    "\n",
    "- **$k_T$**: because $k_T = \\min(p_{T,i}, p_{T,j})\\,\\Delta R_{ij}$, large values mark pairs that are both hard and well separated. In the Hbb jet, those larger values spread over a broader region, which is what you expect from a harder two-prong structure.\n",
    "\n",
    "- **$z$**: values near 0.5 mean the two particles have similar transverse momentum. The Hbb jet keeps relatively large $z$ values across a wider block, while the QCD jet falls off faster away from the diagonal. That tells you the leading Hbb particles share momentum more evenly.\n",
    "\n",
    "- **$m^2$**: off-diagonal regions with larger invariant mass are where separated particles combine into a heavy system. The Hbb jet shows a broader set of moderate-to-large combinations; the QCD jet is more irregular and dominated by a few hot spots.\n",
    "\n",
    "These matrices are the raw input to ParT's pair embedding. Before any learned attention weights appear, the geometry and momentum sharing of the jet are already encoded here."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## Section 3: How ParT Uses These Features\n",
    "\n",
    "### Standard Transformer Attention (Notebook 1)\n",
    "\n",
    "The attention formula from Notebook 1:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\alpha_{ij} = \\text{softmax}\\left(\\frac{Q_i \\cdot K_j}{\\sqrt{d}}\\right)$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The attention weight $\\alpha_{ij}$ depends only on the learned representations $Q_i$ and $K_j$. The model discovers physics relationships through training alone.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Particle Transformer Attention\n",
    "\n",
    "ParT adds one term:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\alpha_{ij} = \\text{softmax}\\left(\\frac{Q_i \\cdot K_j}{\\sqrt{d}} + U_{ij}\\right)$$\n",
    "\n",
    "$U_{ij}$ is an **interaction bias**, computed by a small MLP (the **pair embedding**) from the four pairwise features:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$U_{ij} = \\text{MLP}\\left(\\Delta R_{ij},\\; k_{T,ij},\\; z_{ij},\\; m^2_{ij}\\right)$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The pair embedding outputs one value per attention head, telling each head how strongly two particles should interact based on their physics relationship."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Design Properties\n",
    "\n",
    "Three properties of this design:\n",
    "\n",
    "**1. Additive, not replacing.** $U_{ij}$ is added to the standard $Q \\cdot K$ logits. The model retains full content-based attention; the physics features provide an informed starting point.\n",
    "\n",
    "**2. Permutation equivariant.** $U_{ij}$ depends on the kinematics of particles $i$ and $j$, not their position in the input list. Reordering particles permutes the rows and columns of $U$ accordingly.\n",
    "\n",
    "**3. (Approximately) Lorentz invariant.** The pairwise features ($\\Delta R$, $k_T$, $z$, $m^2$) are Lorentz-invariant or approximately so. Lorentz invariance is built into the architecture rather than learned from data.\n",
    "\n",
    "### The Full ParT Pipeline\n",
    "\n",
    "The Particle Transformer has two information streams.\n",
    "\n",
    "The first stream is the familiar transformer input: per-particle features such as $p_T$, $\\eta$, $\\phi$, and energy are embedded into learned token vectors.\n",
    "\n",
    "The second stream is new: for every particle pair $(i,j)$, the model computes physics-motivated features like $\\Delta R_{ij}$, $k_{T,ij}$, $z_{ij}$, and $m^2_{ij}$. A small pair-embedding network turns those into the interaction bias $U_{ij}$.\n",
    "\n",
    "Inside each transformer block, the usual attention scores $QK^T / \\sqrt{d}$ are shifted by that bias. After several particle-only blocks, a class token is added, two final blocks let it gather jet-level information, and a classification head maps the result to jet labels."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Exercise 2: Implementing the Modified Attention\n",
    "\n",
    "Given pre-computed standard attention scores and interaction biases, add the bias to the scores. One line."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def particle_transformer_attention(Q, K, U, mask=None):\n",
    "    \"\"\"Compute Particle Transformer attention weights.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Args:\n",
    "        Q: query vectors, shape (n_particles, d_k)\n",
    "        K: key vectors, shape (n_particles, d_k)\n",
    "        U: interaction bias, shape (n_particles, n_particles)\n",
    "        mask: boolean mask, shape (n_particles,) -- True for real particles\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Returns:\n",
    "        attention_weights: shape (n_particles, n_particles)\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    d_k = Q.shape[-1]\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Standard attention scores\n",
    "    scores = Q @ K.T / np.sqrt(d_k)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # === YOUR CODE HERE (1 line) ===\n",
    "    # Add the interaction bias to the attention scores\n",
    "    scores = ...  # FILL IN\n",
    "    # ================================\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Mask out padded particles (set to -inf so softmax gives 0)\n",
    "    if mask is not None:\n",
    "        scores = np.where(mask[None, :], scores, -1e9)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Softmax\n",
    "    exp_scores = np.exp(scores - scores.max(axis=-1, keepdims=True))\n",
    "    attention = exp_scores / exp_scores.sum(axis=-1, keepdims=True)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    return attention\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
