   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## Section 4: The Class Token -- From Particles to Jets\n",
    "\n",
    "After the transformer blocks, we have one embedding vector per particle: $\\{h_1, h_2, \\ldots, h_N\\}$. We need a single vector for the classification head.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Option 1: Mean Pooling (Notebook 1)\n",
    "\n",
    "Average all particle embeddings: $h_{\\text{jet}} = \\frac{1}{N}\\sum_i h_i$. Simple, but treats all particles equally in the final aggregation.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Option 2: Class Token (ParT)\n",
    "\n",
    "Following BERT (Devlin et al., 2019), ParT introduces a learnable **class token** (CLS) -- a virtual particle with no physical counterpart. It joins the sequence in the last 2 transformer layers, attends to all real particles, and accumulates a jet-level summary through attention. The final CLS representation is passed to the classification head.\n",
    "\n",
    "The CLS token enters late, after the real particles have already interacted through 8 transformer blocks."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
