   "source": [
    "### Reading the Visualization\n",
    "\n",
    "The top row shows the jet in the $\\Delta\\eta$-$\\Delta\\phi$ plane. Dot size tracks $p_T$. Each red edge points from one particle to the particle that receives its largest attention weight in the selected head.\n",
    "\n",
    "The bottom row shows the same information as a matrix. Read it column-wise: a bright vertical band means many query particles are sending attention to the same key particle. In the semileptonic top example on the right, that effect is extreme: one particle acts as a hub, and the reported mean top-1 weight is 0.80. In the H$\\to$4q and top$\\to$bqq examples, the attention is still concentrated, but it is shared across a few different hubs instead of collapsing onto one.\n",
    "\n",
    "That is the main lesson from this figure. Even though attention is allowed to spread over all particle pairs, the trained model often chooses a much sparser pattern. The head shown here is the most concentrated head in layer 6 for each jet, so it is meant to make that behavior easy to see.\n",
    "\n",
    "For the full analysis -- jet declustering with `fastjet`, attention averaged over many jets, and head-by-head studies -- see [aaronw5/Interpreting-Particle-Transformers](https://github.com/aaronw5/Interpreting-Particle-Transformers) and [arXiv:2412.03673](https://arxiv.org/abs/2412.03673)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Connection to Traditional Observables\n",
    "\n",
    "The patterns ParT discovers through attention are closely related to traditional jet substructure observables developed over decades:\n",
    "\n",
    "| What ParT Learns | Traditional Observable | What It Measures |\n",
    "|:---|:---|:---|\n",
    "| Binary attention clusters | **N-subjettiness** ($\\tau_N$) | How N-pronged is the jet? |\n",
    "| Pairwise momentum correlations | **Energy correlation functions** ($e_N$) | N-point correlations of particle momenta |\n",
    "| Subjet mass via attention grouping | **Jet mass, soft-drop mass** | Mass of the jet or groomed jet |\n",
    "| Hard splitting identification | **Splitting scales** ($\\sqrt{d_{12}}$) | Scale of the hardest splitting |\n",
    "\n",
    "ParT learns these relationships from data in a unified framework (attention) and can combine them in ways that would be difficult to achieve by hand-engineering observables."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## Section 7: Why ParT Works -- Design Principles\n",
    "\n",
    "Three design principles behind ParT's performance:\n",
    "\n",
    "**1. Physics-informed inductive bias.** Lorentz-invariant pairwise features give the model a strong prior. It does not need to learn Lorentz invariance from data -- it is built into the architecture.\n",
    "\n",
    "**2. Permutation equivariance.** Jets are unordered sets. The ParT architecture -- standard attention, interaction bias, and class token aggregation -- respects this symmetry at every level. No model capacity is spent learning an already-guaranteed invariance.\n",
    "\n",
    "**3. Informed attention initialization.** The interaction bias $U_{ij}$ directs the model toward physically relevant particle pairs from the start of training, rather than exploring all $n^2$ possible attention patterns."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Performance on JetClass\n",
    "\n",
    "Results on the JetClass benchmark (10 jet types, from Qu et al. 2022):\n",
    "\n",
    "| Model | Accuracy | Approach |\n",
    "|:---|:---:|:---|\n",
    "| PFN (Deep Sets) | 93.6% | Set function, no particle interactions |\n",
    "| P-CNN | 94.0% | Jet image convolution |\n",
    "| ParticleNet | 95.7% | Graph neural network with edge convolutions |\n",
    "| Plain Transformer | 95.9% | Standard self-attention (Notebook 1) |\n",
    "| **Particle Transformer** | **96.4%** | Self-attention + physics interaction bias |\n",
    "\n",
    "Relative to a plain transformer, ParT adds explicit pairwise physics information and changes how the jet-level summary is formed. In this benchmark, that moves accuracy from 95.9% to 96.4%. At this level, a 0.5-point gain means roughly 12% fewer misclassified jets. The gap is especially valuable on harder class pairs such as Hbb versus Hcc."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## Section 8: Summary\n",
    "\n",
    "The main tutorial points are these:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. A Particle Transformer is still a transformer. The key change is that attention scores receive an extra learned bias built from pairwise physics features.\n",
    "\n",
    "2. The four pairwise inputs are physically meaningful: $\\Delta R$ says who is nearby, $k_T$ says which pairs reflect hard splittings, $z$ says how evenly momentum is shared, and $m^2$ says which pairs combine into a heavy system.\n",
    "\n",
    "3. Those features already contain visible substructure before training. The learned model then decides how to use them inside attention.\n",
    "\n",
    "4. In the trained ParT model, attention is often much sparser than a generic softmax would suggest. That makes the model easier to interpret in terms of jet substructure.\n",
    "\n",
    "5. Adding physics structure helps both performance and interpretability without giving up the core transformer machinery.\n",
    "\n",
    "### References\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Qu, Li, and Qian, \"Particle Transformer for Jet Tagging,\" 2022 ([arXiv:2202.03772](https://arxiv.org/abs/2202.03772))\n",
    "2. Wang et al., \"Interpreting Transformers for Jet Tagging,\" 2024 ([arXiv:2412.03673](https://arxiv.org/abs/2412.03673))\n",
    "3. Vaswani et al., \"Attention Is All You Need,\" 2017 ([arXiv:1706.03762](https://arxiv.org/abs/1706.03762))\n",
    "4. Qu and Gouskos, \"ParticleNet: Jet Tagging via Particle Clouds,\" 2020 ([arXiv:1902.08570](https://arxiv.org/abs/1902.08570))\n",
    "5. Devlin et al., \"BERT: Pre-training of Deep Bidirectional Transformers for Language Understanding,\" 2019 ([arXiv:1810.04805](https://arxiv.org/abs/1810.04805))"
   ]
